description:
The following parameters are rejected by libmongoc and no write is added to the bulk object; however, a debug log message is the only indication of failure.

h4. Update document contains dotted keys but no dollar keys

{code}
<?php

$b = new MongoDB\Driver\BulkWrite;
$b->update(['x'=>1], ['y.x'=>1]);
var_dump(count($b));
{code}

{noformat}
int(0)
{noformat}

libmongoc logs the following warning:

bq. mongoc_bulk_operation_replace_one(): replacement document may not contain $ or . in keys. Ignoring document.

h4. Replacement document with multi=true

{code}
<?php

$b = new MongoDB\Driver\BulkWrite;
$b->update(['x'=>1], ['y'=>1], ['multi' => true]);
var_dump(count($b));
{code}

{noformat}
int(0)
{noformat}

libmongoc logs the following warning:

bq. mongoc_bulk_operation_update(): update only works with $ operators.

Currently we can go from BSON->JSON value, and PHP->BSON->JSON but not PHP->JSON.

It seems like its not a big deal, needing the intermedied BSON format, but it is bigger deal then I first realized as people want to simply json dump their objects for APIs for example.

{code:php}
echo json_encode($model);
{code}

When $model contains ObjectID, the ObjectID will be serialized as empty.

{code:php}
<?php

class Person implements JsonSerializable {
    protected $id;
    protected $name;

    function __construct($name) {
        $this->id = new MongoDB\BSON\ObjectID();
        $this->name = (string)$name;
    }

    function JsonSerialize() {
        $arr = array(
            "name" => $this->name,
            "id"   => $this->id,
        );
        return $arr;
    }
}

$p = new Person ("Jon Jonsson");

var_dump(json_encode($p));
{code}

{code}
string(30) "{"name":"Jon Jonsson","id":{}}"
{code}


This could have been worked around by allowing BSON\fromPHP() serialization of BSON\Type objects since they always result in a fully qualified json object, e.g.:

{code:javascript}
{ "$oid" : "56213654bd21b96c3e4e31c1" }
{code}

So the jsonSerialize() function would become:
{code:php}
    function JsonSerialize() {
        $arr = array(
            "name" => $this->name,
            "id"   => $this->id,
        );

        $bson = MongoDB\BSON\fromPHP($this->id);
        $json = MongoDB\BSON\toJSON($bson);

        $arr["id"] = $json;

        return $arr;
    }

{code}

and would result in:
{code:javascript}
{"name":"Jon Jonsson","id":{ "$oid" : "56213746bd21b9718b1d7371" } }
{code}

Per discussion in the PR for PHPC-459:

{quote}
The Extended JSON spec currently states that a UTCDateTime should yield:

{noformat}
{"$date": {"$numberLong": "<ms since epoch as an integer>"}}

Alternative, optional format:

{"$date": {"$isoDate": <ISO-8601 date string in UTC as a string>}}
{noformat}

I'm opting to use the first format as ISO-8601 has issues representing the full range of dates supported by the BSON date type (as discussed during the previous driver team meeting). Additionally, the {{$numberLong}} format is much easier to generate.

HHVM currently yields the {{$isoDate}} format, which I think we should change. Discussion is ongoing in the spec about whether drivers should always yield {{$numberLong}} and optionally provide a {{$isoDate}} purely for user readability purposes (i.e. it will never be parsed for the authoritative value).
{quote}

Per discussion in the PR for PHPC-459:

{quote}
libbson currently converts Javascript types to JSON by returning its code field as a string value (see: CDRIVER-1335). It also does not properly parse `$code` and `$scope` fields when converting JSON to BSON, which causes the JSON we produce here to be read by libbson as a normal embedded document.

HHVM currently mimics libbson (see: HHVM-156); however, I think we should change its behavior to comply with the Extended JSON spec rather than libbson, which should itself be fixed in 1.6.0.
{quote}

The driver currently does not validate documents for insert or update:

{code}
$bulk = new MongoDB\Driver\BulkWrite;
$bulk->insert(['foo.bar' => 1]);
$bulk->insert(['x' => ['foo.bar' => 1]]);

$manager = new MongoDB\Driver\Manager(URI);
$manager->executeBulkWrite('test.foo', $bulk);
{code}

libmongoc's bulk write API does not validate documents for us. We will want to use the same logic (and validation flags) found in the relevant libmongoc collection methods.
